<p>The intention was to deliver a self-guided, personalized, relationship-based planning experience through a web assessment quiz that adapts to various screen sizes in order to inspire and fulfill career aspirations. This tool was also expected to serve as an entry point for planning via personalized content, and stir curiosity for a potential modality. The end result would be integrated into a "well" section of the clients home page while keeping the user stationary thus resisting the need for a page refresh, or new URL produced.</p>

{{! ---- PROCESS ---- }}
<h3>Indentifying Building Blocks</h3>
<p>Through the use of a supplied project brief containing criteria for success, content, and general functionality, we started by identifying user flow with content as the guide. This content document expressed each portion of the quiz that included questions, suggested input methods, and results of user entered data.</p>

<figure class="figure-site">
	<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/legos.jpg" alt="">
	<figcaption><small>Deciding what parts make up the whole.</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Using <a href="http://atomicdesign.bradfrost.com" target="_blank">Atomic Design</a> philosophies, we began with white board sketches to visually identify neccesities & building blocks of the interface. This process helped to catalog patterns in isolation thereby minimizing the interface to only the essential pieces. Creating the foundation in this fashion also helps developers build for portability, maintainability and modularity thus impacting the capability to iterate efficiently within a succinct code base.</p>

<p>It was equally important to understand not only how each portion of the interface is presented on large screens, but the ability to adapt within smaller contexts as well. By combining both thought processes the interface could easily transfer between each with ease therby providing the user with the best experience and control.</p>

{{! ---- CREATING---- }}
<h3>Wireframing & Prototyping</h3>

<p>Creating wireframes to outline user flow was prepared in Sketch without the inclusion of visual aesthetics; some would also call this the "gray box technique." Each series of questions were examined carefully to assist in indentifying the best way for displaying information. The ability to <a href="https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2017/04/symbols-sketch">create symbols in Sketch</a> was certainly an ally throughout the process in order to provide efficiency in regards to iterations and feedback.</p>

<figure class="figure-site">
	<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/sketch-wireframe.png" alt="">
	<figcaption><small>Sketch File of Wireframe Comps </small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Maintaining wireframes in their most simplistic form avoided discussions revolving around aesthetics as not to hinder the core goals; creating a fluid, and sensible experience for the user. This method aided the group in determining input methods for each series of questions based on ease of use, and adaptability across a variety of screens alleviating discussion revolving around favorite color, or font face.</p>

<figure class="figure-site">
