	<figcaption><small><a href="https://vimeo.com/255285256">Syncing Designs with Sketch</a> from <a href="https://vimeo.com/atomicapp">Atomic</a></small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>A prototype depicting interactions & flow was created with <a href="https://atomic.io">Atomic</a> to guide and educate visually how a user traverses, and interacts during the quiz experience. Discussions such as how users return to particular points of quiz, selects answers, and accesses each input method within different screen contexts were examined. This helped to maintain a sensible process towards the final results screen. Placement was also discussed to help honor the flow of users traversing through each point of the experience. Since Atomic works quite well with Sketch it allowed for quick syncing between multiple Sketch artboards, and designs allowing new content to be pushed rapidly with ease.</p>

{{! ---- Challenges ---- }}
<h3>Challenges</h3>

<p>While not all portions of this project presented an array of challenges, there were certainly a few that had to be addressed.</p>

<figure class="figure-site" style="width: 100%;margin: auto;">
	<div class="flex-inline">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/multiple-choice.png" alt="">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/dropdown-selected.png" alt="">
	</div>
	<figcaption><small>Multiple Choice vs. Select Menu</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The screenshots displayed above show a multiple choice selection for the quiz. While having multiple choice is completely acceptable, it also presents a problem for smaller screens, and requires more cognitive overhead for the user to scroll though results where real-estate is at a premium. Ultimately, we opted for a select menu making it easier on the user, and keeping them isolated within the space they're present in. This decision supplied simplicity for developers coding by not requiring the switch from a select menu to multiple choice on larger screens; its a one size fits all solution.</p>

<figure class="figure-site" style="width: 100%;margin: auto;">
	<div class="flex-inline">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/results-stacked.png" alt="">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/results-column.png" alt="">
	</div>
	<figcaption><small>Results Screens and Variations</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Variations of each results screen required critical thinking and consideration regarding different layouts and contexts. It was imperative to look at diffrent approaches of displaying information that still remained beneficial for readability, but also made sense from an information hierarchy perspective. For the results with information stacked we decided smaller contexts would have the ability to swipe, or click to the next result saving screen real estate, and avoiding the user from scrolling.</p>

<p>The multi-column approach allowed for easy scanning of the data from left to right, but in smaller contexts the information would be displayed as a single column. In this case we decided to hyper link to the CTAs just under the first result giving users the option to  automatically scroll to CTAs efficiently and intuitively. This also avoided CTAs from becoming lost and forgotten by keeping the user focused.</p>

